node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sara Kuburic on July 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'the criticized child: @millennial.therapist/SaraKuburic Sara Kuburic We constantly criticize ourselves We frequently judge others We strive to be perfect We perceive vulnerability as weakness We don't trust ourselves to make decisions We have hard time showing compassion (to self or others) We seek external validation We struggle to accept a compliment We avoiding doing things we can fail at We are hard on ourselves We are hyper-sensitive to criticism from others'.

node.text:
Being overly criticized as a child will manifest in the relationships we build with ourselves and with others. We often become adults who have internalized the critical voice of our caregivers. It’s time to change the narrative ❤️ 

#millennialtherapist

May be an image of text that says '10 things that steal our self-confidence: Sara Kuburic; @millennial.therapist Seeking external validation Comparing ourselves to others Setting unrealistic goals Engaging in negative self-talk Procrastinating Lacking boundaries (e.g. social media) Dwelling on our mistakes Internalize other people's opinions of us Perceiving feedback as criticism Giving in to fear'.

node.text:
Self-confidence is trusting our ability or capacity to do something successfully (achieve a goal, accomplish a task, attract attention, etc.). It’s important to note that someone’s trust in their ability doesn’t always translate to self-esteem or self-love. Why? Because we can value a certain capacity/trait but still not value who we are as a whole. 


The most common topic surrounding self-confidence is related to the way we look. In the Body Shop’s Global Self-Love Index women said that self-image concerns lessens their confidence, as does seeing models in advertisements or influences/celebrities on social media. It also shows that women with high self-love think that their relationships and the state of the world are more important than their appearance and how others see them.


To learn more, check out @thebodyshop Self-Love Campaign!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sara Kuburic on July 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'examples of self-betrayal in relationships: Sara Kuburic; @millennial.therapist @millennial. Morphing into who our partner wants us to be •Denying problems in the relationship Accepting less than we deserve Ignoring our intuition •Engaging in undesired intimacy Compromising our beliefs Sacrificing our values Losing our autonomy Apologizing for things that are not our fault Silencing ourselves to keep the status quo Constantly prioritizing their needs above our own'.

node.text:
It’s tempting to self abandon for a relationship. What we fail to understand is that no one can replace the relationship we have with ourselves.
